// This is an example of how to use OWL's *temporary* file IO.
// This IO system is definitely going to change, it was only implemented
// temporarily to have something to mess around with for the v0.0.1 release.

// Create a new temporary directory
Path temp = newTempDirectory();

// Create a sub-directory called test.
Path test = temp.createDirectory("test");

// Let's see what the directory path actually is.
println($"Test directory: {test}");

// Get a new path pointing to a specific child in the directory.
// Path file1 = test.getChild("file1.txt"); would also work.
Path file1 = test / "file1.txt";

println($"Writing to: {file1}");
println(); // Just some nice spacing in the output.

// Replace the entire file with the given text.
file1.writeText("Hello there!");

// Let's read it back now.
text contents = file1.readText();

// Remember OWL treats text as grapheme clusters.
// If you modify the example to have emojis and such, the length may surprise you a little.
println($"Length: {contents.Length}");
println($"Content: {contents}");

// We should clean up out temp directory here just to be nice.
// However I felt a bit scared about adding a delete function right now xD.
